{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/find-linear-transformation-based-on-known-points-64785e987db0", "time": 1683002483.7860968, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/find-linear-transformation-based-on-known-points-64785e987db0/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Find Linear Transformation Based on Known Points | by Gergely D. N\u00e9meth | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Find Linear Transformation Based on Known Points", "description": "This story shows how to identify a linear transformation based only on the transformation of a few points. For the math in this story, I used this work of Alexander Nita, and descriptions from\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://math.colorado.edu/~nita/MatrixRepresentations.pdf", "anchor_text": "this", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "http://math.colorado.edu/~nita/index.html", "anchor_text": "Alexander Nita", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_map", "anchor_text": "Wikipedia (linear map)", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1m9ctAIKwFYTe6ecTdvUaqrFFC-15PVRM", "anchor_text": "this Google Colab.", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harris_Corner_Detector", "anchor_text": "Harris corner detection", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_map", "anchor_text": "Linear map", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "http://math.colorado.edu/~nita/index.html", "anchor_text": "Alexander Nita", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://math.colorado.edu/~nita/MatrixRepresentations.pdf", "anchor_text": "work", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.linalg.solve.html", "anchor_text": "numpy.linalg.solve()", "paragraph_index": 10}], "all_paragraphs": ["This story shows how to identify a linear transformation based only on the transformation of a few points. For the math in this story, I used this work of Alexander Nita, and descriptions from Wikipedia (linear map). For codes, see this Google Colab.", "Example: Let\u2019s suppose that we have a moving object in the 3D space. We have two timestamps of the object and we want to identify the transformation that can move the object from the first state to the second state. If we know the position of 3 points in each state (e.g. Harris corner detection), we can define the matrix of the transformation.", "Linear transformation (linear map, linear mapping or linear function) is a mapping V \u2192W between two vector spaces, that preserves addition and scalar multiplication. \u2014 Wikipedia (Linear map)", "Formally, for vector spaces V, W over the same field K, the function f: V \u2192W is a linear map if any two vectors u,v \u2208 V and any scalar c \u2208 K satisfies the two following conditions:", "If V and W are finite-dimensional vector spaces and a basis is defined for each vector space, the linear map f can be represented by a transformation matrix. If M is a m x n then (3): f(x)=Mxdescribes a linear map R\u207f\u2192R\u207f\u207f.", "If f: V \u2192W is a linear map,", "The linear mapping f can be determined by f(v\u2081),\u2026,f(v\u2099), thus using the a\u1d62\u2c7c coefficients. The matrix M is", "If we use the [v]\u2090 notation for the representation of v vector in a basis, the matrix representation of the linear transformation in ordered bases:", "For the proof of the following important equation, see Alexander Nita\u2019s work. It states that multiplying with M matrix the v vector represented in \u03b2 basis transforms to f(v) represented in \u03b3 basis.", "Therefore, if we have a vector v, a basis in both vector space(V, W) and m points with {v, f(v)} pair we can determine linear transformation. For this, we have to know, how to transform the points into the first basis in V, then, calculate the matrix M and finally transform from the second basis back to the standard basis (if we want to).", "To get [v]\u2090 for basis a, we can use the numpy.linalg.solve() function:np.linalg.solve(np.transpose(a), v)", "To get the matrix representation in ordered bases, we simply put the above equation into numpy terms: The function lin_map_matrix produces M using the matrix FV of f(v\u2081),\u2026,f(v\u2099) and the matrix W of w\u2081,\u2026,w\u2098.", "The function linmap_predict calculates the v vector\u2019s representation for V basis, then transforms it using the M matrix multiplication and get the standard basis representation using W.", "If we have an n and an m dimensional vector space and we know a basis in both space (n and m vectors respectively that are linearly independent) and m points in both spaces, then if it exists, we can determine the linear mapping between the spaces.", "In a special case, if we have 3 points in the 3D space (not in a line) and we know their representation after a linear transformation, we can determine the linear transformation.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F64785e987db0&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffind-linear-transformation-based-on-known-points-64785e987db0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffind-linear-transformation-based-on-known-points-64785e987db0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=regist